  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is Cyprus's non-dom tax status?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Non-domiciled (non-dom) residents pay no tax on foreign dividends and interest for 17 years. You qualify if you weren't a tax resident in Cyprus for 17 of the past 20 years. This makes Cyprus attractive for investors and those with passive income. Consult a local tax advisor for specifics.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Cyprus in the Schengen Area?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Cyprus is an EU member but not in the Schengen Area. Your Cyprus residence permit does not grant automatic travel rights to Schengen countries. You'll follow standard visa rules for your nationality when traveling to Schengen Europe.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I access GESY (public healthcare) with the DNV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not initially. Digital Nomad Visa holders must use private health insurance. GESY is for residents who contribute 2.75% of their income. DNV holders may be able to enroll after establishing longer-term residency, but shouldn't count on it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long can I stay on Cyprus's Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Up to 3 years total. The initial visa is for 1 year and can be renewed twice for additional 1-year periods. After 3 years, you'd need to apply through a different visa category for longer stays.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is English really widely spoken in Cyprus?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. English is an official language due to British colonial history. You can conduct daily life, banking, healthcare, and government services entirely in English. Street signs are in both Greek and English. This is a major advantage for English-speaking nomads.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Which city in Cyprus is best for digital nomads?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Limassol is the most international with the largest expat community, best restaurants, and beach lifestyle—but also most expensive. Paphos is more affordable and popular with British retirees. Nicosia (capital) has more traditional Cypriot feel and lower rents. Larnaca is budget-friendly with good airport access.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

